caption: Sadly, we did not have a great experience with this company. We placed an online order for a family of five. The order wasn't ready when it was scheduled to be and they ignored the requested items for toppings. Most concerning was that the gluten-free crust was not gluten free! This is especially troubling as so many people  have gluten allergies. (And it can really spoil a vacation to have a reaction!) When we went to pick up, the kitchen was in chaos and our order was being burned. I'm sure they were exhausted from the previous weekend being the Super Bowl. In any case,  Jamay (manager?) was kind and tried to make it right. He gave me a cell phone number and told me to text the next day to get a refund.  When I did, I received no reply. Bottom line:  if you say you are gluten free be gluten-free.  If you say you will refund,  refund. Business is much easier and customers are much happier when you just do what you say you will do.

I was tracking the total we spent and was prepared for it in my bank account.  But the transaction was not processed until over 4 months...24 Sep 2020 is when it cleared my bank. Visited during the GMF 2020 event while waiting for our favorite band to perform. In walking distance to the Riverfront, park and museums. Outdoor seating for people watching and tv’s for sport watching alike.  I have walked past this establishment quite a bit over the years and was always curious at their take on pizza. Was under the impression they served slices but to our dismay, they did not. The personal size is probably the equivalen to a large slice in NYC or even Westshore but the price isn’t slice priced. Definitely, a downtown price point.  Ordered the White pizza, personal size to share as a snack. The size was cut into 4 small parts. The dough was fresh and free formed, artisanal style. Flavors were pretty great, but the overall “White” style wasn’t what you would expect, if you’re a fan of such flavors. Either the cook wasn’t familiar with the recipe or .... frankly IDK. It may have been baked too long? Any longer and we would have had a true slice size. The dough shrunk considerably.... IMO I’ll have to give it a go another time to critique precisely. It was tasty enough to scarf down & tie us over but I did expect a more true to recipe, even if it was “their” own take on a “White” style pie.  The waitstaff was as efficient as you would expect during what seemed like a full days rush. Even offered us water with our To-Go order. Not many places care enough to extend even water to smaller orders.  Bathroom was a HOT mess and hadn’t been tended to for hours, it seemed. No TP and trash overflowing.  Worth the visit. Expect a hurried atmosphere when local events are happening.

The gluten-free pizza was absolutely AMAZING! The crust was so buttery and delicious. Definitely the best gluten free crust I've ever had that wasn't homemade. The pesto bread was delicious, and we had the large Ricky Bobby and it was incredible! The gluten-free chicken tenders were really good. My husband said they were the best he's ever had, though I found the breading to be a bit too hard for my liking. The gelato was divine! We had both the chocolate and the vanilla. It tasted like Talenti gelato. The gluten-free brownies were a bit too tacky (gooey but not like regular gooey brownies) and not quite flavorful enough. I think they use too much starch in their recipe. If you've had Dunkin Donuts gluten-free brownies, it tastes a lot like them. The Nutella dessert pizza was really good, though a bit hard to chew. Definitely best when fresh.  You seat yourself and they bring you menus and utensils. It's pretty crowded. The tables are very close together and there's no possible way the bar could be fully seated if the table behind it is too. It took only a few minutes for the server to take our order. We waited about 20 minutes between ordering and getting our food. I had asked for dessert to be brought out after dinner, but they brought it out less than 5 minutes after bringing the pizzas and chicken tenders. Still giving 5 stars though because the food more than made up for it.  Spent about $95 with tip on all of the above, plus a small gluten-free cheese pizza, a coke, and an Honest peach tea. It more than fed our family of 2 adults and 2 usually very picky kids who don't often eat much when we go out, but scarfed down their dinner this time! We took home half of each pizza and most of the Nutella dessert pizza, plus half of the large order of chicken tenders.

Horrible service and waitstaff don’t know what they’re doing at all. I come in and there’s a huge blob of people just standing around, no clear line is forming. Someone says there’s a list we could put our name on to get seated in the order in which we arrived. I ask one of the waitstaff (blonde woman with glasses) if there’s a list I could put my name down on and she said “one second, but not really”. She never gets back to me so I assume there’s no list. So then someone else comes in and they’re a party of 6. They ask another waiter about the list and it turns out there IS a list. They get to put their names ahead of my own even though my boyfriend and I had already been there standing with no clear answers for 5+ minutes. There had been TWO tables for two that were empty since we arrived that could have been for my boyfriend and I. They take the two chairs from one of those tables for the group of 6. The other table was also missing a chair but they could have EASILY grabbed another chair from another table which was not being used at the time (common sense, anyone?!) FINALLY we get seated at the table that was missing one chair because someone finally figured out that they could simply move a chair a few feet so we could be seated. This place is a mess. They were also out of ice. Really, ice? You’re out of frozen water? They also were not understaffed at all, I saw at least 4 waitresses working today and this place really isn’t all that big. All in all it took over 15 minutes for us to be seated despite two tables for two being available since we arrived, and waitresses had no system for seating parties, just a big disorganized mess. You need to retrain your staff or hire people who actually know something, anything, about waitering and hospitality.  Someone working here also told another party over the phone that the place was closing at 8pm tonight but the New Years hours are clearly stated on google maps as closing at 9pm.......even more confusion  Edited to add that the food took 40 minutes to come (it was just two personal pizzas), there are not nearly enough chairs for all the tables that are in here, they messed up our order switching the fresh garlic and roasted garlic on our orders, portion sizes were tiny, my sun dried tomatoes were burnt because the pizza is not actually thin crust (if it was thin crust pizza the crust would have cooked quickly enough so that my toppings didn’t get completely scorched, the crust was thick.) the bathrooms are gross and unsanitary, soap dispensers were broken off of the wall and sitting on the floor. I seriously have never been to a worse establishment.
Look at these bathrooms, these are the only two in the establishment.
Employees CANNOT wash hands after using the restroom (after wiping with paper towels because there’s no toilet paper) due to the fact that the soap dispensers have been ripped off of the walls.

The food is phenomenal every time, but the staff seems to become less and less friendly. One time I was charged twice and while awaiting a refund, I was charged an NSF fee. The manager at the time (this was a while ago) said if I “didn’t have enough to eat out, then I shouldn’t.” How disrespectful. How I chose to spend the last few bucks in my account isn’t his business, and isn’t it a compliment that I would chose to spend it on this establishment? I didn’t return for a while. Until I moved into the area. Recently on May 10, my friend and I wanted to enjoy some delicious pizza and wings. I realized we showed up with about 40 minutes left of the shop being open, but I didn’t expect to be treated so rudely. The girl (with red or orange hair) said she is only taking to-go orders. And later was complaining to the other employee in front of my friend and I about “why there were all these people coming in so late, don’t they know they close at 11pm.” We left outside to go eat, and when we went back inside to order drinks, the employee (with blonde hair) “greeted” us by saying “What?” I was confused — did we do something to offend her? I said was “excuse me, did you just say ‘what’?” And all she could say to play it off was “What’s up?” I get it that you want to go home and you’re tired, we’ve all been there. But blatant rudeness is unacceptable. The employee looked so nervous as to what I might say or react, but by that time, my friend and I had had enough and tried to salvage our outing for the night by not escalating the situation. I love the pizza and the wings — this is one of my favorite spots in all of Tampa, but it keeps getting spoiled by poor employee-customer experiences.
